      "Fields that depend on long-horizon thinking are especially affected by this problem. In public health, in urban planning, in the management of large institutions, the consequences of a decision may not become visible for a decade. The professional who was present for both the decision and its eventual outcome holds a kind of knowledge that no one who arrived after the fact can reconstruct from records alone. They know not just what happened but what it felt like to watch it happen slowly, and that felt dimension often contains the most useful signal about what to do differently next time.",
